00:01:44.600 --> 00:01:51.167
Hydrogen has a nucleus with one
proton, therefore it has a

00:01:51.167 --> 00:01:56.700
single positive charge and
typically has one electron

00:01:56.700 --> 00:02:01.367
with a negative charge
going around it.

00:02:01.367 --> 00:02:06.267
There are two famous isotopes
of hydrogen.

00:02:06.267 --> 00:02:09.067
One is deuterium, and
one is tritium.

00:02:09.067 --> 00:02:11.067
I'm not going to talk about
tritium today, but I'm going

00:02:11.067 --> 00:02:14.300
to talk about deuterium.

00:02:14.300 --> 00:02:17.133
It has one proton
and one neutron.

00:02:17.133 --> 00:02:19.333
This has a mass of one.

00:02:19.333 --> 00:02:21.167
This has a mass of two.

00:02:21.167 --> 00:02:24.700
But notice it still has just one
positive charge, so it has

00:02:24.700 --> 00:02:27.467
just one electron
going around it.

00:02:27.467 --> 00:02:30.167
So chemically, the two
are identical.

00:02:30.167 --> 00:02:33.900
They have the same electronic
orbitals, and they'll bond and

00:02:33.900 --> 00:02:36.900
so on in just the way--in
the same way that

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:39.933
the other one does.

00:02:39.933 --> 00:02:44.033
The other one I want to
think about is oxygen.

00:02:47.567 --> 00:02:50.867
Oxygen typically has eight
protons and eight neutrons.

00:02:53.400 --> 00:02:55.900
Because of eight protons, it
has eight positive charges.

00:02:55.900 --> 00:02:59.867
It'll have eight electrons
going around it.

00:02:59.867 --> 00:03:02.067
And that will determine its
chemical properties.

00:03:04.633 --> 00:03:07.800
And this would be called
oxygen 16.

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:08.733
Sorry.

00:03:08.733 --> 00:03:13.833
Oxygen 16, because that
mass adds up to

00:03:13.833 --> 00:03:17.100
16 atomic mass units.

00:03:17.100 --> 00:03:22.733
The other one we're interested
in has 8 protons and 10

00:03:22.733 --> 00:03:25.867
neutrons, adding up
to a mass of 18.

00:03:25.867 --> 00:03:30.000
Still has eight protons,
therefore has eight electrons.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.067
Same chemical properties, but a
different mass, and this one

00:03:34.067 --> 00:03:37.067
is called oxygen 18.

00:03:37.067 --> 00:03:42.100
And by convention, that mass
number is put to the upper

00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:52.300
left of the letter symbol
for that element.

00:03:52.300 --> 00:03:55.500
So oxygen 16 and oxygen 18.

00:03:55.500 --> 00:03:58.733
Now, we're interested
in water.

00:03:58.733 --> 00:04:03.100
So the question is what water
molecules can we make from

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:04.067
these isotopes?

00:04:04.067 --> 00:04:08.567
And by far the most common would
be normal H2O, which

00:04:08.567 --> 00:04:16.167
would have oxygen 16 plus two
hydrogens coming off it.

00:04:16.167 --> 00:04:18.733
Water vapor has a
dihedral shape.

00:04:18.733 --> 00:04:20.367
It's not a linear molecule.

00:04:20.367 --> 00:04:24.333
The hydrogens droop off
it at an angle.

00:04:24.333 --> 00:04:28.633
That's by far the most common,
because this is much more

00:04:28.633 --> 00:04:34.233
common than that by a factor
of 1,000 or so.

00:04:34.233 --> 00:04:36.300
And this is much more common
than that by a

00:04:36.300 --> 00:04:39.333
factor of 1,000 or so.

00:04:39.333 --> 00:04:44.100
So if you just randomly put
these molecules--these atoms

00:04:44.100 --> 00:04:47.367
together to form molecules,
almost everything is going to

00:04:47.367 --> 00:04:53.067
be like this, but there are
going to be some that have

00:04:53.067 --> 00:05:00.700
this structure where you replace
one of the hydrogens

00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:03.133
with a deuterium.

00:05:03.133 --> 00:05:06.967
Notice that this has a mass
of 18, because it's

00:05:06.967 --> 00:05:10.667
16 plus 1 plus 1.

00:05:10.667 --> 00:05:15.067
This is going to have a mass
of 19, because it's

00:05:15.067 --> 00:05:19.367
16 plus 2 plus 1.

00:05:19.367 --> 00:05:22.500
And then the other one is where
you replace the oxygen

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:27.933
16 with oxygen 18 but keep both
of these as hydrogens.

00:05:27.933 --> 00:05:30.200
That's going to be 18, 19, 20.

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:33.033
So that's going to have
a mass of 20.

00:05:33.033 --> 00:05:35.567
Now you can imagine others.

00:05:35.567 --> 00:05:40.133
For example, you could replace
both of the hydrogens with

00:05:40.133 --> 00:05:44.000
deuterium, but that would
be so rare that I'm not

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:45.033
interested in it.

00:05:45.033 --> 00:05:48.767
Or you could replace the oxygen
16 by 18 and one of the

00:05:48.767 --> 00:05:53.300
hydrogens by deuterium, but
again, that is so rare that

00:05:53.300 --> 00:05:54.967
I'm not interested in it.

00:05:54.967 --> 00:05:57.333
So I'm going to just
limit myself

00:05:57.333 --> 00:06:02.233
to these three isotopes.

00:06:02.233 --> 00:06:05.833
This would be called the normal,
and these would be the

00:06:05.833 --> 00:06:06.633
heavier ones.

00:06:06.633 --> 00:06:08.567
And we keep track
of the ratio.

00:06:08.567 --> 00:06:12.167
For example, if you're comparing
these in a sample,

00:06:12.167 --> 00:06:15.000
you would measure
the D/H ratio.

00:06:17.800 --> 00:06:21.433
Or if you're comparing these
two, you would take the ratio

00:06:21.433 --> 00:06:26.500
of oxygen 18 to oxygen 16.

00:06:26.500 --> 00:06:29.900
And the higher this is, you
would say--the common

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:34.933
terminology is that the water
is heavy if it has a large

00:06:34.933 --> 00:06:38.833
deuterium to hydrogen ratio,
or it's heavy if it has a

00:06:38.833 --> 00:06:43.967
large oxygen 18 to oxygen 16
ratio, or light if it's got a

00:06:43.967 --> 00:06:47.100
lower than usual ratio
of deuterium.

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:50.800
So I'm going to be using these
terms heavy and light in a

00:06:50.800 --> 00:06:57.633
relative fashion to describe
whether these ratios are

00:06:57.633 --> 00:07:02.800
typical for ocean water or
larger or smaller than that.

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:07.633
So I hope you've Googled or gone
back to your high school

00:07:07.633 --> 00:07:10.367
or college chemistry book
and reviewed this.

00:07:10.367 --> 00:07:17.267
Now, isotopes also appear some
isotopes are so-called

00:07:17.267 --> 00:07:18.733
radiogenic isotopes.

00:07:18.733 --> 00:07:23.133
They are temporary isotopes that
can be formed by nuclear

00:07:23.133 --> 00:07:25.600
reaction and then decay
automatically

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:28.033
with some half life.

00:07:28.033 --> 00:07:31.967
Those are called unstable,
or radiogenic, isotopes.

00:07:31.967 --> 00:07:34.533
And maybe those are the isotopes
you've heard about

00:07:34.533 --> 00:07:36.667
before, but I'm not talking
about those.

00:07:36.667 --> 00:07:40.700
These are called stable
isotopes, because they remain.

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:43.933
They don't have any
natural decay.

00:07:43.933 --> 00:07:48.467
They just exist in these
different mass forms, and they

00:07:48.467 --> 00:07:53.733
persist over millions and
billions of years.

00:07:53.733 --> 00:07:55.033
So these are the stable
isotopes--in this case, I

00:07:55.033 --> 00:07:58.200
would call these the stable
isotopes of water, which is

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:02.500
what I've labeled this slide.

00:08:02.500 --> 00:08:03.767
Any questions on that?

00:08:06.367 --> 00:08:11.700
So now for our purposes, it's
very important to know that

00:08:11.700 --> 00:08:17.233
the heavier isotopes, these
two, have a slightly lower

00:08:17.233 --> 00:08:19.167
vapor pressure.

00:08:19.167 --> 00:08:21.867
Because they're heavier, they
move a little more slowly in

00:08:21.867 --> 00:08:26.200
the liquid, which means they
evaporate more slowly than

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:28.967
this, but they would
condense more

00:08:28.967 --> 00:08:32.867
readily than normal water.

00:08:32.867 --> 00:08:35.767
Therefore, when you do get a
phase change, when you get

00:08:35.767 --> 00:08:40.100
vapor going to liquid or you
get liquid going to vapor,

00:08:40.100 --> 00:08:41.900
there will be a fractionation.

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:43.733
This is the other new word.

00:08:43.733 --> 00:08:47.000
A fractionation means a process
where you change the

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:50.500
ratios of these two things.

00:08:50.500 --> 00:08:55.133
For example, if you had a bucket
of nuts in your room

00:08:55.133 --> 00:08:59.733
peanuts and cashews and your
roommate happened to be a

00:08:59.733 --> 00:09:05.167
cashew lover, so when she was
grabbing a fistful of nuts,

00:09:05.167 --> 00:09:08.967
she would tend to get one that
had more cashews in it, that's

00:09:08.967 --> 00:09:10.333
a fractionation process.

00:09:10.333 --> 00:09:13.833
What's being left behind then
is going to be a little bit

00:09:13.833 --> 00:09:19.600
heavier, a little more enriched
in the peanuts and a

00:09:19.600 --> 00:09:23.400
little bit more depleted in
the cashews, because she's

00:09:23.400 --> 00:09:25.800
grabbing out her
favorite nuts.

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:27.967
That's what's going on when
you're evaporating or

00:09:27.967 --> 00:09:29.167
condensing water.

00:09:29.167 --> 00:09:33.433
You're changing the ratio of
peanuts to cashews by the way

00:09:33.433 --> 00:09:37.400
you're doing that thermodynamic
transformation,

00:09:37.400 --> 00:09:43.400
vapor to liquid or liquid
back to vapor.

00:09:43.400 --> 00:09:45.200
That's what we're going
to be tracking today.

00:09:48.367 --> 00:09:52.067
Now, the way we keep track of
these ratios is with the

00:09:52.067 --> 00:09:54.100
so-called called
delta notation.

00:09:57.067 --> 00:10:02.667
We have to define a reference
ratio of D/H. And that's

00:10:02.667 --> 00:10:04.967
standard mean ocean water.

00:10:04.967 --> 00:10:07.800
It's basically a sample
of several

00:10:07.800 --> 00:10:08.967
places around the ocean.

00:10:08.967 --> 00:10:13.900
They collect, mix them all
together, and store large

00:10:13.900 --> 00:10:18.600
volumes of it in laboratories,
and use that as a reference

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:23.333
every time they're doing an
isotope ratio measurement.

00:10:23.333 --> 00:10:25.833
So that's called--the
abbreviation for that is SMOW,

00:10:25.833 --> 00:10:28.633
standard mean ocean water.

00:10:28.633 --> 00:10:34.767
Then you measure the D/H ratio
in the sample of interest,

00:10:34.767 --> 00:10:40.800
divide it by the D/H ratio in
your reference liquid, SMOW,

00:10:40.800 --> 00:10:45.633
subtract 1, multiply by 1,000,
and that is so-called the

00:10:45.633 --> 00:10:47.000
delta D value.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.233
If it's deuterium, it's delta
D. If you do the same thing

00:10:50.233 --> 00:10:55.633
with oxygen, it's the
delta O-18 value.

00:10:55.633 --> 00:10:58.033
And that's what we'll
be tracking.

00:10:58.033 --> 00:11:00.467
So notice the way this
is subtracted.

00:11:00.467 --> 00:11:05.667
So if you had a sample that had
a larger ratio of D/H than

00:11:05.667 --> 00:11:09.800
the reference, that would end
up being a positive number.

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:11.200
And we would call that--

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:14.600
we'd say the sample is
heavier than SMOW.

00:11:14.600 --> 00:11:19.433
If the D/H ratio is less than
the standard, then the number

00:11:19.433 --> 00:11:22.000
is going to turn out to be
negative, and we're going to

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:26.967
say that sample is lighter
than SMOW.

00:11:26.967 --> 00:11:30.967
This quantity is usually stated
as per mill or written

00:11:30.967 --> 00:11:36.300
not with a percent sign but with
a percent sign with two

00:11:36.300 --> 00:11:37.567
zeros on the bottom.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:45.833
So again, a reservoir of liquid
water under evaporation

00:11:45.833 --> 00:11:49.600
will become isotopically heavier
because the lighter

00:11:49.600 --> 00:11:53.600
isotopes will evaporate
more readily.

00:11:53.600 --> 00:11:56.767
A reservoir of water vapor
imagine some water vapor in

00:11:56.767 --> 00:12:00.433
this room, and we're condensing
out some of it

00:12:00.433 --> 00:12:04.900
that's going to be isotopically
heavier--sorry,

00:12:04.900 --> 00:12:08.433
lighter, because the heavier
isotopes are condensing out

00:12:08.433 --> 00:12:10.567
and leaving preferentially.

00:12:14.967 --> 00:12:17.767
You can do these experiments
in the laboratory.

00:12:17.767 --> 00:12:20.267
You could take a
dish of water.

00:12:20.267 --> 00:12:21.733
Take a sample from it.

00:12:21.733 --> 00:12:23.967
Put it into a mass spectrometer
to determine the

00:12:23.967 --> 00:12:25.400
isotope ratios.

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:27.233
Then let it sit there
for a few days

00:12:27.233 --> 00:12:29.833
and partially evaporate.

00:12:29.833 --> 00:12:31.933
And when you came back and took
another sample of the

00:12:31.933 --> 00:12:37.900
liquid that would be this case
and again put it on the mass

00:12:37.900 --> 00:12:41.200
spectrometer to get the isotope
ratio, it would be

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:44.400
heavier--isotopically heavier,
because the lighter isotopes

00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:48.700
would have evaporated
preferentially.

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:53.267
So it's an easy thing to do in
the laboratory to measure this

00:12:53.267 --> 00:12:57.800
physical process called
isotope fractionation.

00:12:57.800 --> 00:13:02.867
Now, in the real world, if you
start with an ocean value of

00:13:02.867 --> 00:13:08.467
zero, the delta D value, or the
delta O-18 value would be

00:13:08.467 --> 00:13:11.833
zero, which is likely, right,
because ocean is our modern

00:13:11.833 --> 00:13:16.133
reference for isotope ratio.

00:13:16.133 --> 00:13:19.767
So typically, the delta values
for modern ocean are going to

00:13:19.767 --> 00:13:22.967
be very close to zero.

00:13:22.967 --> 00:13:25.733
When you evaporate, the
isotopes--the lighter isotopes

00:13:25.733 --> 00:13:29.500
evaporate preferentially, and
so the vapor you have in the

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:33.000
atmosphere is typically going to
be lighter than the ocean.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.467
It will have a negative
delta value.

00:13:35.467 --> 00:13:39.767
And then as you condense water
out, the rain is going to be

00:13:39.767 --> 00:13:42.233
heavier than the vapor.

00:13:42.233 --> 00:13:45.167
So if the vapor is minus 10,
the rain is going to be

00:13:45.167 --> 00:13:46.067
heavier than that.

00:13:46.067 --> 00:13:49.033
Let's say minus 3.

00:13:49.033 --> 00:13:51.967
The remaining vapor after you've
removed some of the

00:13:51.967 --> 00:13:57.200
liquid is going to be lighter
still, because you've removed

00:13:57.200 --> 00:13:58.900
some of the heavier isotopes.

00:13:58.900 --> 00:14:03.367
Then if you rain again from
that lighter vapor, the

00:14:03.367 --> 00:14:08.800
precipitation is going to be
heavier than that vapor but

00:14:08.800 --> 00:14:14.900
lighter than the rain that
fell out before.

00:14:17.467 --> 00:14:20.467
And the vapor remaining is
going to be even lighter,

00:14:20.467 --> 00:14:25.100
because you've removed heavier
isotopes of the vapor that you

00:14:25.100 --> 00:14:26.300
started with.

00:14:26.300 --> 00:14:30.400
So this is the progressive
fractionation process.

00:14:33.700 --> 00:14:34.800
